page.title: 06Listed Buildings Page 2
page.content: IVY HOUSE: built 1570 faces up Pound Hill is now the village social club established 1909. (Grade II) RECTORY: parts date back to the reign of Queen Anne, was renamed Witchampton House following the erection of the new vicarage, badly damaged by fire on 13 February 1983 leaving only the original shell,now restored.(Grade II) ROSE LEA: a thatched and timber framed cottage opposite church. Until the early part of the 20th century there was a cobbler, John Sumner, who lived and worked at Rose Lea. (Grade II) THE OLD HOUSE: possibly an early 15th or 16th century Hall house with open hearth and central fireplace. Adjacent to the church, it is thatched and timber framed, infilled with red brick it was converted into a house with upstairs accomodation. (Grade II)
